Admittedly, not the best pictures but too good not to share with you. The yummiest tomato soup with homemade breadcrumbs.

Roasted tomato soup

Market
Tomatoes
One white onion
Six cloves of garlic
One shallot thinly sliced
Olive oil
Fresh thyme
Salt and pepper to taste
1 teaspoon chili flakes

Wash and cut a mixture of three tomatoes. I used cherry, vine ripened, and compari tomatoes. Throw into baking dish with cut up onion, garlic, shallot, olive oil, and fresh thyme. Salt and pepper to taste and add chili flakes depending on how much heat you want in your soup.

Method
Bake at 400° until the tomatoes start to blister. Stir and add back to the oven. Remove once everything is nice and browned. 

Add mixture to a blender and blend until creamy. Transfer to a sauté pan with a minimum of 12 ounces of chicken broth. I used bone broth made from scratch at home that I like to freeze and save for this very reason. Bring to a boil, then lower to a simmer. Salt and pepper to taste and add any additional seasonings. I added a Bayleaf. You can also add a bit of heavy cream at this time for a bisque.

I then took Panko with Italian seasoning, garlic powder, onion powder, and a drizzle of olive oil and browned in the oven.

Serve warm in a bowl with a dusting of the Panko seasoning on top. Best served beside a grilled cheese sandwich.

Born- Kristy Marie Hendersen
1974, Libra. French/Swedish/Armenian/German. Catholic

California native and raised. The 3 things that define me? I am a mother, wife and {girl-girl} twin. I love the ocean, Wobbie and I live at the beach with our two tea cup Maltese and I dream of having a fancy goldfish I can name cricket. I describe myself as a grown up hippie... I am obsessed with romanticizing my life. I imagine each day has its own soundtrack. More times than not, it is Native American flute music. (My best friend turned me onto that.) I absolutely love setting a mood. Pouring a glass of wine, clipping fresh herbs from the garden, opening all the French doors, and creating a meal. 

I retired last August after 30 years in the beauty industry. The last seven owning a full service salon inland. I still love all things industry related. And I am a self described product whore. I don't get paid to share things on social media. I truly do it because I believe in the things I find along the way and want to share.

8 years ago today I bought, rebuilt and expanded a full service salon. Hair-skin-nails, all the good stuff. We were one of Orange County's largest and well known. It was the salon I worked at as a single mother in my 20's and 30's. Where I met some of my best friends and believe it or not, Wobbie ♥️ (even though he thought the receptionist, my best friend was hot and didn't even look twice at me). I worked from the moment, my eyes opened until I shut them at night seven days a week 365 days a year. 

I was so grateful for each person that worked with me. Everyone brought some thing new and exciting to the space. We shared so many memories together. Babies were born, marriages were made, our family members passed on, and we shared these life moments together. 

I poured blood sweat and tears in to that business. And I mean real tears 😭. Crocodile tears… The kind of sobbing that makes your breaths skip on the way in and out.  I could write a book about it. There was a feeling of pure pride in what I was able to build inside those walls. It took a piece of my soul with it. 

This was my retirement 🍾

Famous La Scala Salad from famed Beverly Hills restaurant 🍽️🌴

Salad
3 heads Romain lettuce washed and thinly sliced
2 packages salami, thinly sliced.
1 cup mozzarella cheese on the super fine great
1 can fresh artichoke hearts, quartered.
One canned garbanzo beans, rinsed 

Dressing
3 tablespoons red wine vinegar.
2 heaping teaspoons Dijon mustard
1/2 cup olive oil
1/4 cup fresh, grated and ground Parmesan cheese (releases the flavor)
Fresh cracked pepper and salt to taste 

Because this dinner party was impromptu I wanted to get as much of my prep done that morning so I could assemble everything fresh that evening. That's why I put all the ingredients in separate bowls lined with a paper towel to absorb all the moisture. Nothing worse than a soggy salad. You want all the ingredients to retain their integrity and the flavor of your dressing to shine through.

10 Days until it's time to set the table and gather with the family. I still don't know how I will dress the table this year... The table is in the foyer now (as the builder intended) but we haven't had a meal in here for 6 years so it's a learning curve 🦃🍽️

MARKET
1 loaf of sourdough bread cubed
Fresh herbs like parsley, oregano, and thyme.
One carton turkey stock.
One cube of butter (maybe more)
1 large diced white onion,
1.5 cups chopped celery.
Quarter cup olive oil,
Salt and pepper.

What I really think set this stuffing a part from others was the fresh loaf of sourdough from the French Market. We have one on Del Mar @chaupainbakery 🥖 for locals.  Two key ingredients would be, using turkey stock versus chicken broth and fresh herbs versus dried. 

I sliced the loaf of sourdough and left it out overnight to get "stale". Next 
Cube and drizzle with olive oil, salt, pepper and fresh herbs. Lay this out on a baking sheet and bake at 400° to crisp up. You will need to toss intermittently for even crispness. Remove from oven and set aside. 

Take 1/2 your cube of butter and melt in sauté pan. Then add your onions and celery. You want to cook these just enough to soften. Now you can add your croutons and sautéed vegetables together. Toss them in a bowl and start adding your turkey stock. I really feel like this step is up to the person. How dense and how moist you like your stuffing is up to preference. Then I poured this mixture into individual baking dishes. Because the crispy caramelized top was most important to me. I added my butter here. So I sliced the remaining half of cube and placed on top. I baked the stuffing at 350° until golden brown on top.

I baked mine in individual serving dishes, so that everybody got to experience the layers of flavor and texture.

Me pretending I speak French 🇫🇷

New Year's Eve we sat around the new lounge area in the house and my girlfriends husband wanted us to say a word. Our word for 2024. I struggled to communicate what my word would be. I threw out growth and even selfishness. There was a third word, but I can't remember what it was for the life of me… It was pretty late, and I had enough wine. But I knew I wasn't articulating what I wanted to say or what my word was. 

And then I woke up the next morning to another girlfriend sending me my word. It is "space". Space to create, space to breathe, space to nurture and space to grow. 

Last year was as isolating as it was suffocating. It was a true struggle for me. Most artistic people think too much. Absorb too much. And tend to get "stuck". So the idea of space to create and get unstuck gives me an excitement for this next chapter. 

What's your word?
